2. Text Processing and Streams

> Text Processing Tools:
    Powerful commands for searching, filtering, and transforming text
 
grep - Pattern Searching
  - grep 'pattern' file: Search for a specific pattern in a file
    - Example: grep 'root' /etc/passwd
  - grep -i 'pattern' file: Perform a case-insensitive search
    - Example: grep -i 'linux' readme.txt
  - grep -r 'pattern' /path: Search for pattern recursively in directories
    - Example: grep -r '127.0.0.1' /etc/
  - grep -v 'pattern' file: Invert match to show non-matching lines
    - Example: grep -v '#' config.conf
  - grep -n 'pattern' file: Prefix each line of output with its line number
    - Example: grep -n 'error' /var/log/syslog
  - grep -c 'pattern' file: Suppress normal output and show count of matching lines
    - Example: grep -c 'failed' auth.log
  - grep -E 'regex' file: Interpret pattern as an extended regular expression
    - Example: grep -E 'apple|orange' fruit.txt
  - grep -w 'word' file: Match only whole words
    - Example: grep -w 'is' document.txt
  - grep -A 3 'pattern' file: Print 3 lines of trailing context after matching lines
    - Example: grep -A 3 'start' boot.log
  - grep -B 3 'pattern' file: Print 3 lines of leading context before matching lines
    - Example: grep -B 3 'end' boot.log

sed - Stream Editor
  - sed 's/old/new/' file: Replace the first occurrence of a pattern per line
    - Example: sed 's/bash/zsh/' script.sh
  - sed 's/old/new/g' file: Replace all occurrences of a pattern per line
    - Example: sed 's/temp/final/g' data.txt
  - sed -i 's/old/new/g' file: Edit the file in-place (saves changes to file)
    - Example: sed -i 's/localhost/127.0.0.1/g' /etc/hosts
  - sed '5d' file: Delete the 5th line of the file
    - Example: sed '5d' users.list
  - sed '1,5d' file: Delete a range of lines from 1 to 5
    - Example: sed '1,5d' log.txt
  - sed -n '10,20p' file: Print only a specific range of lines (10 to 20)
    - Example: sed -n '10,20p' database.csv
  - sed '/pattern/d' file: Delete all lines matching the pattern
    - Example: sed '/# comment/d' config.py
  - sed 's/^/prefix/' file: Insert text at the beginning of each line
    - Example: sed 's/^/DEBUG: /' app.log
  - sed 's/$/suffix/' file: Append text to the end of each line
    - Example: sed 's/$/;/' main.c

awk - Pattern Scanning
  - awk '{print $1}' file: Print the first field (column) of each line
    - Example: awk '{print $1}' names.txt
  - awk '{print $1,$3}' file: Print multiple specific fields
    - Example: ls -l | awk '{print $9, $5}'
  - awk -F: '{print $1}' /etc/passwd: Define a custom field separator
    - Example: awk -F: '{print $1}' /etc/passwd
  - awk '$3 > 100' file: Filter lines based on a numeric condition in a field
    - Example: awk '$3 > 500' stats.txt
  - awk '{sum+=$1} END {print sum}': Perform arithmetic operations and print final result
    - Example: awk '{sum+=$3} END {print sum}' sales.log
  - awk 'NR==5' file: Print a line based on its record number (line number)
    - Example: awk 'NR==10' data.csv
  - awk 'length > 80' file: Print lines that exceed a certain character length
    - Example: awk 'length > 100' source_code.c
  - awk '/pattern/ {print $2}' file: Print a specific field only for matching lines
    - Example: awk '/active/ {print $2}' services.log

Other Text Tools
  - cut -d: -f1 file: Extract fields using a delimiter
    - Example: cut -d: -f1 /etc/group
  - cut -c1-10 file: Extract a specific range of characters
    - Example: cut -c1-8 passwords.txt
  - sort file: Sort lines of text alphabetically
    - Example: sort list.txt
  - sort -n file: Sort lines based on numeric value
    - Example: sort -n scores.txt
  - sort -r file: Reverse the result of the sort
    - Example: sort -r names.txt
  - sort -u file: Sort and remove duplicate lines (unique)
    - Example: sort -u access.log
  - uniq file: Report or omit repeated adjacent lines
    - Example: sort list.txt | uniq
  - uniq -c file: Prefix lines by the number of occurrences
    - Example: sort category.txt | uniq -c
  - tr 'a-z' 'A-Z': Translate or delete characters (lowercase to uppercase)
    - Example: echo "hello" | tr 'a-z' 'A-Z'
  - tr -d '0-9': Delete specific characters from the input
    - Example: echo "pass123" | tr -d '0-9'
________________________________________________________________________________________

> I/O Redirection & Pipes:
    Controlling input/output streams and chaining commands

Output Redirection
  - command > file: Redirect standard output to a file, overwriting existing content
    - Example: ls /etc > list.txt
  - command >> file: Redirect standard output to a file, appending to existing content
    - Example: echo "New entry" >> log.txt
  - command 2> file: Redirect standard error (stderr) to a file
    - Example: ls /root 2> error.log
  - command &> file: Redirect both standard output and standard error to the same file
    - Example: tar -czf backup.tar.gz /data &> backup.log
  - command 2>&1: Redirect stderr to the same location as stdout
    - Example: my_script.sh > output.log 2>&1
  - command > /dev/null: Discard output by sending it to the "null device" (black hole)
    - Example: ping -c 4 8.8.8.8 > /dev/null
  - command 2>&1 | tee file: Display output on screen and save it to a file simultaneously
    - Example: make 2>&1 | tee build_output.txt

Input Redirection
  - command < file: Read input for a command from a file instead of the keyboard
    - Example: mysql database_name < backup.sql
  - command << EOF: Use a "Here Document" for multi-line input until the EOF string
    - Example: cat << EOF > hello.txt
  - command <<< 'string': Use a "Here String" to pass a single line of text as input
    - Example: base64 -d <<< 'SGVsbG8='

Pipes and Command Chaining
  - cmd1 | cmd2: Pass the standard output of cmd1 as standard input to cmd2
    - Example: history | grep "chmod"
  - cmd1 && cmd2: Execute cmd2 only if cmd1 finishes successfully (exit code 0)
    - Example: make && ./install.sh
  - cmd1 || cmd2: Execute cmd2 only if cmd1 fails (exit code non-zero)
    - Example: mkdir folder || echo "Folder already exists"
  - cmd1 ; cmd2: Execute cmd2 immediately after cmd1, regardless of the outcome
    - Example: date ; sleep 5 ; date
  - Example: ps aux | grep nginx | awk '{print $2}' - Get nginx PIDs
    - Use case: Lists all processes, filters for nginx, and extracts the second column (PID)
  - Example: cat file | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn - Frequency count
    - Use case: Reads a file, sorts lines, counts unique occurrences, and sorts by frequency descending
________________________________________________________________________________________

> Process Management:
    Monitoring and controlling running processes

Viewing Processes
  - ps: Show processes associated with the current terminal session
    - Example: ps
  - ps aux: Show all processes from all users with detailed information (CPU, Memory, etc.)
    - Example: ps aux | grep firefox
  - ps -ef: Show all processes in a full-format listing, including the parent PID (PPID)
    - Example: ps -ef --forest
  - ps -u username: Display all processes owned by a specific user
    - Example: ps -u student
  - pstree: Display the running processes as a hierarchical tree structure
    - Example: pstree -p
  - top: Provide a real-time, interactive view of running processes and system resources
    - Example: top
  - htop: An enhanced, colorized, and user-friendly version of top (requires installation)
    - Example: htop
  - Interactive top commands:
    - k: Kill a process by PID
    - r: Change the priority (renice) of a process
    - q: Quit the interactive viewer
  - top -u username: Filter the real-time monitor to show only one user's processes
    - Example: top -u root

Process Control
  - kill PID: Send the SIGTERM (15) signal to request a graceful shutdown
    - Example: kill 1234
  - kill -9 PID: Send the SIGKILL (9) signal to force an immediate termination
    - Example: kill -9 1234
  - kill -15 PID: Explicitly send the SIGTERM signal (standard behavior of kill)
    - Example: kill -15 1234
  - killall process_name: Send a signal to all processes identified by their exact name
    - Example: killall sleep
  - pkill pattern: Send a signal to processes based on a pattern or attribute
    - Example: pkill -u dan python
  - Ctrl+C: Send the SIGINT (2) signal to interrupt the current foreground process
    - Use case: Stopping a ping command in the terminal
  - Ctrl+Z: Send the SIGTSTP (20) signal to suspend the foreground process
    - Use case: Pausing a text editor to return to the shell
  - bg: Resume a suspended process in the background
    - Example: bg %1
  - fg: Bring a background or suspended job to the foreground
    - Example: fg %1
  - jobs: List all active jobs associated with the current shell session
    - Example: jobs -l
  - command &: Execute a command in the background immediately
    - Example: updatedb &
  - nohup command &: Run a command that persists even after the terminal is closed (ignores SIGHUP)
    - Example: nohup ./long_script.sh &

Process Priority
  - nice -n 10 command: Launch a new process with a specific "niceness" value
    - Example: nice -n 10 tar -czf backup.tar.gz /data
  - Nice values: Range from -20 (highest priority/least nice) to 19 (lowest priority/most nice)
  - renice -n 5 -p PID: Modify the priority of an already running process
    - Example: sudo renice -n -5 -p 1234
  - Default value: All processes start with a default nice value of 0
  - Permissions: Regular users can only increase nice values; only root can set negative values
________________________________________________________________________________________

> Basic Networking Commands:
    Network configuration and diagnostics

Network Configuration
  - ip addr show: Display all network interfaces and their assigned IP addresses
    - Example: ip addr show eth0
  - ip link show: Show the status of network interfaces (Up, Down, MTU)
    - Example: ip link show wlan0
  - ip route show: Display the kernel's routing table (gateway and routes)
    - Example: ip route show
  - ifconfig: Legacy tool to display or configure network interface parameters
    - Example: ifconfig
  - ifconfig eth0 up/down: Enable or disable a specific network interface
    - Example: sudo ifconfig eth0 down
  - hostname: View or temporarily modify the system's network hostname
    - Example: hostname
  - hostname -I: Display all network addresses assigned to the host
    - Example: hostname -I

Network Diagnostics
  - ping host: Send ICMP Echo Request packets to test network connectivity
    - Example: ping google.com
  - ping -c 4 host: Limit the number of echo requests sent to exactly four
    - Example: ping -c 4 8.8.8.8
  - traceroute host: Print the route (hops) that packets take to reach a network host
    - Example: traceroute yahoo.com
  - tracepath host: Trace the path to a destination, discovering MTU along the way (no root required)
    - Example: tracepath google.com
  - mtr host: A real-time, interactive tool that combines ping and traceroute
    - Example: mtr 8.8.8.8
  - netstat -tuln: Display listening TCP and UDP ports in numeric format (no DNS lookup)
    - Example: netstat -tuln
  - netstat -an: Show all active and listening network connections
    - Example: netstat -an | grep :80
  - ss -tuln: Modern and faster replacement for netstat, showing listening sockets
    - Example: ss -tuln
  - ss -s: Provide a summary of socket statistics (TCP, UDP, RAW, etc.)
    - Example: ss -s

File Transfer
  - wget URL: Download a file from the internet directly to the current directory
    - Example: wget https://kernel.org/pub/linux/kernel/v5.x/linux-5.0.tar.xz
  - wget -c URL: Resume a partially downloaded file from where it stopped
    - Example: wget -c https://example.com/bigfile.iso
  - curl URL: Transfer data from or to a server (displays content in terminal by default)
    - Example: curl https://ifconfig.me
  - curl -O URL: Save the downloaded file using its original remote filename
    - Example: curl -O https://example.com/file.zip
  - curl -o file URL: Save the downloaded file under a custom local filename
    - Example: curl -o setup.sh https://example.com/install.sh
  - scp file user@host:/path: Securely copy a file to a remote host over SSH
    - Example: scp script.sh student@192.168.1.50:/home/student/
  - scp -r dir user@host:/path: Recursively copy an entire directory to a remote location
    - Example: scp -r project/ backup_user@server:/backups/
  - rsync -avz source dest: Synchronize files/directories efficiently (archive mode, verbose, compressed)
    - Example: rsync -avz Documents/ /backup/Documents/
